(this shows how even the words you choose can change the tone of the message to mislead people)\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003edon't trust science, scientists don't.\u003cbr\u003ewe only trust it after we try everything we can think of to disprove it but it keeps standing and gets even more solid with time.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eif you look at people with panic attacks, coffee is probably really badbut for some people it can be good in a very specific way.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003ethat's not contradiction. \u003cbr\u003ereal science will never be "Coffee is BAD/GOOD for you!!!" that's clickbait titles of articles butchering early-stage research.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003escience is specific and if you read an actual science study, you'll see how it has absolutely nothing to do with those clickbait articles.",
              "textOriginal": "\u200b@xaero76 research happens simultaneously.\n\nit's not all scientists doing one thing at once. \n\n\nthere are hundreds of groups os researchers, each one does many research projects, most take years to finish, some finish faster when other researchers publish something that doesn't seem right, because they focus on that subject and let other projects in the background(when possible, bc a LOT of research needs 24/7 attention)\n\nbtw, media covered science doesn't speak for all of science.\n\nis not because a research is being covered a lot, and is popular that any scientists agree with it, even the author's themselves might be working disproving it soon after publishing. \n\nI've written how you actually find real science(also be wary that it takes months if not years for it to be accepted as solid, \"New research\" is a clickbait term that completely misleads people into believing that's already science just because it was published.\n\n\nbut there's peer reviews, impact of the journal, the academic relevance and trust of/on the authors..\n\nit's not science that is confusing, is your interpretation of what you think is science.\n\nfollow some actual science communicators and full-on scientists on subjects you're interested in, they always cover popular subjects that make the news and explain why \"science news\" isn't good science. \n\ncoffee can kill you..\nbut so can water, which is actually the acid with the highest pH ever, and it's almost 100% dihydrogen monoxide with dirt and without the dirt it is actually more toxic!             "videoId": "1Q9F2-Se0Ss",
            "textDisplay": "I think the biggest problem with trying to do an accent is that there is no such thing as an "American" accent or a "British" accent. I had this realization watching Doctor Who. I couldn't figure out why Peri's accent was driving me crazy until it suddenly hit me that she had done a very good moment of basically a Brooklyn accent followed by a very good moment of a Southern accent.  Taken in isolation, both accents were very credible.  The problem was that my native ear knew those accents weren't the same thing, so it sounded extremely weird to hear them juxtaposed.  In fact, is was so weird that the first several times I heard those parts I didn't even hear the Brooklyn flavor or the Southern flavor.  All I heard was, "Wrong!"  I couldn't even figure out how it was supposed to be an American accent.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe same thing obviously applies to a "British" accent.  My American ear isn't familiar enough with the accent to distinguish between a London accent and a Northern accent and a Cockney accent, for example.
